HOL-13: Conditional Rendering (Part 2), Lists and Keys

Various ways of conditional rendering

If/else statements assigning JSX to a variable before returning it
Ternary operators for compact inline conditions (condition ? A : B)
Logical && operator for showing something only when a condition is true
Returning null to render nothing at all under certain conditions
Multiple methods can be combined within a single component tree, as done in this lab

Rendering multiple components

Several independent components (Book, Blog, Course Details) can be rendered together in one parent
Each component manages its own internal data and rendering logic
The parent component simply arranges and displays each child component
Encourages splitting an app into small, focused, independently testable pieces
Multiple components rendering together is a normal and expected pattern in React apps

List component

A component whose job is to render a collection of items, usually via .map()
Takes an array (often through props) and returns a list of JSX elements
Keeps list-rendering logic separate from the rest of the UI
Was used here for Book Details, Blog Details, and Course Details, each rendering their own array
Improves reusability, since the same list component can render different data sets

Keys in React applications

Keys are special string/number attributes React uses to identify list items uniquely
Help React efficiently determine which items changed, were added, or were removed
Should be stable and unique among siblings, like an id field from the data
Missing or incorrect keys can lead to rendering bugs or performance issues
Are not passed down as props to the component itself; they're used internally by React

Extracting components with keys

When rendering a list, it's common to extract each item into its own component
The key prop must be placed on the outer element inside .map(), not inside the extracted component
Keeps the list-building understandable, especially as list items become more complex
Keys only need to be unique among siblings in the same array, not globally
Applied here to Book, Blog, and Course items, each keyed by their respective id

React Map, map() function

.map() transforms each element of an array based on a provided function
Returns a brand-new array without mutating the original
The standard technique in React for turning data arrays into arrays of JSX elements
Was used across all three components in this lab (books, blogs, courses) to generate list items
Essential for any dynamic, data-driven list rendering in React
